Test that new nodes can join a cluster with existing sharded tables

––– comment –––
Start nodes 1, 2
––– input –––
export INSTANCE=1
––– output –––
––– block: ../../base/replication/start-searchd-precach –––
––– input –––
export INSTANCE=2
––– output –––
––– block: ../../base/replication/start-searchd-precach –––
––– comment –––
Create RF=2 table on 2-node cluster - auto-sharding creates cluster c
––– input –––
mysql -h0 -P1306 -e "CREATE TABLE c:existing_table (id bigint, data string) shards='2' rf='2'"; echo $?
––– output –––
0
––– comment –––
Verify shards exist on both nodes (2 nodes, RF=2 - each node holds both shards)
––– input –––
for i in 1 2; do mysql -h0 -P${i}306 -sN -e "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM system.sharding_table WHERE table = 'existing_table'"; done
––– output –––
2
2
––– comment –––
Start node 3
––– input –––
export INSTANCE=3
––– output –––
––– block: ../../base/replication/start-searchd-precach –––
––– comment –––
Join node 3 to cluster c
––– input –––
mysql -h0 -P3306 -e "JOIN CLUSTER c at '127.0.0.1:1312'"; echo $?
––– output –––
0
––– comment –––
Verify all 3 nodes synced
––– input –––
for port in 1306 2306 3306; do timeout 30 mysql -h0 -P$port -e "SHOW STATUS LIKE 'cluster_c_status'\G" > /tmp/status_$port.log && grep -q "Value: primary" /tmp/status_$port.log && echo "Port $port: Node synced"; done
––– output –––
Port 1306: Node synced
Port 2306: Node synced
Port 3306: Node synced
––– comment –––
Verify cluster now has 3 nodes
––– input –––
mysql -h0 -P1306 -sN -e "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM system.sharding_state"
––– output –––
3
––– comment –––
Wait for cluster to stabilize before cleanup
––– input –––
sleep 15; echo "Cluster stabilized"
––– output –––
Cluster stabilized
––– comment –––
Cleanup - drop table without cluster prefix
––– input –––
mysql -h0 -P1306 -e "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS existing_table"
––– output –––
